b'@calvinfroedge From strictly a Chartist eye:
\xe2\x9c\x85Risk/Reward is perfect:close below $2.10 on weekly chart and re-evaluate...
As low as $1.50 for shit storm support 
\xe2\x9c\x85Weekly close above $3.23 = bullish 
\xe2\x9c\x85Dividend cushion certainly helps make it easy to jump in 
Thx for putting $NGL on my radar\xf0\x9f\x91\x8d'

b"@IrvingSoh Indeed! But like @hkuppy said, most money in investing is made when a hopeless situation turns into a merely bad one. That's what just happened with $BTU and what we should keep an eye on with $NGL."

b'@calvinfroedge Likely a stronger rebound in $NGL\xe2\x80\x99s business when we come out of covid. Obviously thermal side of $BTU\xe2\x80\x99s business a drag in the US but if ESG mandates create a lack of investment it\xe2\x80\x99s possible supply declines as much or more than demand. Developing nations need thermal coal...'

b"@PaulHay86275858 Looks to me like $NGL in much better position than $BTU.  $BTU is hilarious. Don't know the company well but just shows how pessimistic people can be about what until covid was a profitable company. The other side of ESG craziness."
